{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17521721","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17521721"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:36:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:36:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13725"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13725"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.08,0.35,0.38,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6344"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108350"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6344"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13725"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90740"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"2118"},{"type":"tags","id":"2528"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11770"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11858"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43439"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108350"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of worsening dyspnoea, dry cough and fever. She has a history of psoriasis but is otherwise well. She does not take any regular medications and has no known allergies. She started smoking cigarettes two weeks ago. She recently visited a friend who owns pet birds but denies other new exposures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 88% on room air, and temperature 38.4\u00b0C. Auscultation reveals diffuse crackles throughout both lung fields. There are erythematous, well-demarcated plaques with overlying silvery scale on her elbows and knees.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal WCC 14.2 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0) with eosinophils 2.1 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (0.0-0.4), CRP 210 mg/L (\u003C5). Electrolytes and renal function are normal. A chest X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Bacterial pneumonia","Autoimmune interstitial lung disease","Hypersensitivity pneumonitis","Acute eosinophilic pneumonia","Eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe chest X-ray demonstrates diffuse bilateral pulmonary infiltrates. The presentation of acute onset dyspnoea, cough, fever, and diffuse bilateral pulmonary infiltrates in a young patient is suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute eosinophilic pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E. The temporal relationship to starting smoking is a significant clue, as new-onset smoking is a recognised trigger. Other associated factors include newly commenced medications (including antibiotics and NSAIDs), inhaled recreational drugs or occupational inhalants. While peripheral eosinophilia is present in this case, it is important to note that acute eosinophilic pneumonia often presents without peripheral eosinophilia initially, with eosinophilia developing later in the disease course or being found only on bronchoalveolar lavage (BAL). The pathogenesis is incompletely understood, but IL-33 plays a key role, contributing to eosinophil recruitment and degranulation in the lungs. Diagnosis would be confirmed by demonstrating eosinophilia (\u003E25%) on BAL and excluding other causes. Treatment involves avoidance of any contributory agents (tobacco smoke in this case) and consideration of oral glucocorticoid use if required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial pneumonia\u003C/strong\u003E can present similarly with fever, cough and infiltrates, but the diffuse bilateral pattern and presence of eosinophilia (when it occurs) are atypical. Severe pneumonia remains on the differential but is less likely given the overall clinical picture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutoimmune interstitial lung disease\u003C/strong\u003E is generally associated with connective tissue diseases such as rheumatoid arthritis, systemic sclerosis or systemic lupus erythematosus rather than with psoriasis. Autoimmune interstitial lung disease would typically have a subacute to chronic course rather than acute presentation and would be less likely to present with diffuse infiltrates and fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExposure to birds raises the possibility of \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypersensitivity pneumonitis\u003C/strong\u003E. However, the acute presentation with fever and the temporal relationship to smoking initiation are more consistent with acute eosinophilic pneumonia. Typical CT findings in hypersensitivity pneumonitis include centrilobular nodules and ground-glass opacities, and the condition typically presents with a more insidious onset.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis\u003C/strong\u003E (Churg-Strauss syndrome) is a small-vessel vasculitis that can cause pulmonary infiltrates and eosinophilia. However, it typically occurs in patients with asthma and is associated with extrapulmonary manifestations like sinusitis, neuropathy, and palpable purpura, which are not present here.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute eosinophilic pneumonia typically presents with acute onset dyspnoea, cough and fever, with diffuse pulmonary infiltrates on imaging and eosinophilia on bronchoalveolar lavage.","Peripheral eosinophilia is often absent at initial presentation of acute eosinophilic pneumonia, developing later in the disease course.","The diagnosis of acute eosinophilic pneumonia requires exclusion of other causes of pulmonary eosinophilia including parasitic infections, medications, and eosinophilic granulomatosis with polyangiitis."],"references":["De Giacomi F, Vassallo R, Yi ES, Ryu JH. Acute Eosinophilic Pneumonia. Causes, Diagnosis, and Management. Am J Respir Crit Care Med. 2018 Mar 15;197(6):728\u201336. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29206477/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90740"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13725"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20662"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20662"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/NqR7jrg6C3b7jAkzVHdiC6ZhnD4nON.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/NqR7jrg6C3b7jAkzVHdiC6ZhnD4nON.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":734,"height":511}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90740","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90740"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-09T18:27:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-09T18:28:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6344"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108350"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"ite